You can compensate machine translations with good destination language skills, but really good translations/localizations do require good source and destination language skills (and a good proof reader who has at least basic knowledge of the source language and, preferably, superior destination language skills). Further, for a good translation/localization, the translator and proof reader need knowledge about both languages' cultures and colloquialisms.
The sad part is, that some people do make money using machine translations that are sub-par and pretty much just pasted onto the pages.
The differences can usually be noticed in things like text flow and sticking to speech patterns (vocabulary, slangs, accents or similar) different characters use.

Beauty and the Beast rolled live action in the late 80's. I guess you can move the goalpost with "That's not furry enough," but Ron Perlman doesn't look quite human before four hours of makeup so judge for yourself.

Of course, that's a romance piece. What's rare outside of the human-with-a-forehead realm of Star Trek and similar Sci-Fi shows is the human/other couple that are already hooked up, bumping their respective notions of uglies, and are surrounded by a cohort who are adjusted to it.

The issue with mainstreaming "furry" is if it's human enough to be human compatible, just make it a human. If it's not, then it won't fit in with human cultural mores which adds a complication to the writing that needs to pay off to be worth the bother. The best example of that which I can think of is Pilot in Farscape. While the writing worked hard to respect the otherness of its aliens, usually they were human-enough except when an episode was founded on an otherness aspect and ran with it for an hour. Pilot, being an evolved from of a bug/crustacean species unfit for space travel on its own but able to leverage his species' parasitical heritage to become a biological interface for a space-faring life form ship, he was able to fill a properly alien role as something that could interact with the rest of the crew but only through a cultural hole in the wall; he can't leave, they can't understand how he perceives the universe, and their causes and concerns beyond survival have little overlap. This made Pilot interesting, but also a small part of the show.

Take Law & Order and add a doberman person. What do you do with that which can't be done with a human? Color blindness works with humans. Maybe it can "sniff out" a liar? If anything that minor superpower would short-circuit the 40-minute mystery if the audience keeps shouting at the TV, "Call in the dobie and check if he's bullshitting!"

But, maybe someday Seth MacFarlane will do it for the lulz.
